{"response":"The No-Mapping strategy in Clean Architecture is primarily used when defining domain models or external interfaces within a software architecture. It helps to promote modularity, maintainability and separation of concerns by separating these components into clear boundaries.

When the domain model or external interface can be represented using multiple narrow interfaces, it may make sense to use the No-Mapping strategy to ensure that each component is responsible for specific tasks without direct integration with other parts of the system. This approach helps to avoid tight coupling and promotes better design practices by allowing teams to work on individual components independently.

